{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01PLf9XxkV46tvWaqHrtFgC5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01LokiPhMQ4KLjt9CYG6MQWa","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-parallel-execution.md","limit":150},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2579,"cache_read_input_tokens":52202,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2579,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01P6VJWwxyDkdUjYM8CN6t2V","session_id":"8a461711-53e2-475a-88dd-c7013f6080c5","uuid":"58c5761e-c810-4b15-a5c2-677dacd5c51e"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LokiPhMQ4KLjt9CYG6MQWa","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tstepsCompleted: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]\n3\tlastStep: 8\n4\tstatus: 'complete'\n5\tcompletedAt: '2026-04-03'\n6\tinputDocuments:\n7\t  - prd.md (parallel execution PRD, 30 FRs, 13 NFRs)\n8\t  - ux-design-parallel-execution.md (multi-lane TUI UX spec)\n9\t  - architecture-multi-framework.md (workflow engine architecture, brownfield)\n10\tworkflowType: 'architecture'\n11\tproject_name: 'codeharness'\n12\tuser_name: 'BMad'\n13\tdate: '2026-04-03'\n14\t---\n15\t\n16\t# Architecture Decision Document — Parallel Execution\n17\t\n18\t_Extends architecture-multi-framework.md. All prior decisions (driver interface, output contracts, model resolution, TUI components) remain valid._\n19\t\n20\t## Project Context Analysis\n21\t\n22\t### Requirements Overview\n23\t\n24\t**Functional Requirements:**\n25\t30 FRs across 7 capability areas. Core is parallel epic execution via git worktrees (FR6-FR11), merge + validation (FR12-FR17), engine-handled null tasks (FR18-FR21), hierarchical flow model (FR1-FR5), per-epic scope (FR22-FR24), verify flag optimization (FR25-FR26), and multi-lane TUI (FR27-FR30).\n26\t\n27\t**Non-Functional Requirements:**\n28\t13 NFRs. Worktree creation <10s, multi-lane TUI at 15 FPS with 4 lanes, telemetry writes <10ms, merge <30s (non-conflicting), crash isolation between lanes, no orphaned worktrees, backward compatibility at max_parallel=1.\n29\t\n30\t**UX Requirements:**\n31\tMulti-lane TUI with side-by-side lanes (>=120 cols), stacked (80-119), single (<80). Merge status as first-class display element. Lane lifecycle events visible. Telemetry invisible by default. New Ink components: LaneContainer, Lane, CollapsedLanes, SummaryBar, MergeStatus.\n32\t\n33\t**Scale & Complexity:**\n34\t\n35\t- Primary domain: Node.js CLI with multi-process orchestration and git worktree management\n36\t- Complexity level: High — concurrent process management, git branch lifecycle, merge conflict resolution via LLM, hierarchical state machines\n37\t- Estimated new components: ~12 (worktree manager, lane pool, merge agent, hierarchical flow parser, epic completion detector, telemetry writer, 6 new Ink components)\n38\t\n39\t### Technical Constraints & Dependencies\n40\t\n41\t- **Git worktrees** — `git worktree add/remove/list`. Requires git >= 2.15. Each worktree is a separate working directory on a separate branch. Git operations must be atomic per worktree — no concurrent git commands on the same worktree.\n42\t- **Process isolation** — Each lane runs its own workflow engine instance (or async task). Lanes share the sprint-state.json on main only at merge boundaries.\n43\t- **Existing workflow engine** — Currently single-threaded, sequential. Must be refactored to support concurrent instances operating on different working directories.\n44\t- **Ink TUI** — Single React render tree. Multi-lane rendering is layout, not multi-instance. All lanes feed into the same Ink render loop.\n45\t- **State file** — sprint-state.json lives on main branch. Worktree-local state tracks per-epic progress. Merge reconciles worktree state back into main state.\n46\t\n47\t### Cross-Cutting Concerns\n48\t\n49\t1. **Concurrent git operations** — Two worktrees can `git commit` simultaneously (different branches), but `git merge` must be serialized (modifies main).\n50\t2. **State synchronization** — Sprint-state.json on main is the source of truth. Worktree-local state files track epic progress. Merge merges both code and state.\n51\t3. **Resource contention** — Multiple agent dispatches consume API rate limits from the same account. Lane pool must respect global rate limits.\n52\t4. **Error blast radius** — A crash in one lane must not corrupt another lane's worktree or state.\n53\t\n54\t## Starter Template Evaluation\n55\t\n56\t### Selected Starter: Existing codebase\n57\t\n58\t**Rationale:** Brownfield. Extends the workflow engine, adds git and multi-lane orchestration modules.\n59\t\n60\t**New modules to add:**\n61\t\n62\t```\n63\tsrc/lib/\n64\t├── worktree-manager.ts       # NEW — git worktree create/merge/cleanup lifecycle\n65\t├── lane-pool.ts              # NEW — manages concurrent lanes, scheduling\n66\t├── merge-agent.ts            # NEW — dispatches dev agent for conflict resolution\n67\t├── telemetry-writer.ts       # NEW — NDJSON append for per-story telemetry\n68\t├── hierarchical-flow.ts      # NEW — parses story_flow/epic_flow/execution from YAML\n69\t├── epic-completion.ts        # NEW — detects all-stories-done, triggers epic_flow\n70\t\n71\tsrc/lib/ink-lane.tsx          # NEW — Lane component (per-epic workflow view)\n72\tsrc/lib/ink-lane-container.tsx # NEW — LaneContainer (side-by-side layout)\n73\tsrc/lib/ink-summary-bar.tsx   # NEW — SummaryBar (done/merging/pending)\n74\tsrc/lib/ink-merge-status.tsx  # NEW — MergeStatus (conflict resolution display)\n75\tsrc/lib/ink-collapsed-lanes.tsx # NEW — CollapsedLanes (one-line summaries)\n76\t\n77\tsrc/schemas/\n78\t├── workflow.schema.json      # MODIFY — add execution, story_flow, epic_flow sections\n79\t├── telemetry.schema.json     # NEW — NDJSON entry schema\n80\t```\n81\t\n82\t## Core Architectural Decisions\n83\t\n84\t### Decision 1: Worktree Lifecycle Model\n85\t\n86\t**Decision:** Each parallel epic gets its own git worktree on a dedicated branch. The worktree manager handles the full lifecycle: create → execute → merge → validate → cleanup.\n87\t\n88\t**Worktree creation:**\n89\t```bash\n90\tgit branch codeharness/epic-{N}-{slug} main\n91\tgit worktree add /tmp/codeharness-wt-epic-{N} codeharness/epic-{N}-{slug}\n92\t```\n93\t\n94\t**Branch naming:** `codeharness/` prefix prevents collision with user branches (NFR12).\n95\t\n96\t**Worktree location:** `/tmp/codeharness-wt-epic-{N}` — temporary, cleaned up after merge. User-visible in TUI and `codeharness status`.\n97\t\n98\t**Merge flow (serialized — only one merge at a time):**\n99\t```\n100\t1. git checkout main\n101\t2. git merge codeharness/epic-{N}-{slug}\n102\t3. If conflict → dispatch merge agent\n103\t4. If resolved → run test suite\n104\t5. If tests pass → git worktree remove → git branch -d\n105\t6. If tests fail → revert merge, retry agent (up to 3 attempts), escalate\n106\t```\n107\t\n108\t**Rationale:** Git worktrees are the lightest isolation primitive — no clone overhead, shared object store. The `/tmp` location makes cleanup obvious. Branch prefix prevents accidental collision.\n109\t\n110\t### Decision 2: Lane Pool & Scheduling\n111\t\n112\t**Decision:** The engine maintains a fixed-size lane pool. Each lane is an async task (not a separate process) that runs a workflow engine instance against a worktree directory.\n113\t\n114\t**Pool structure:**\n115\t```typescript\n116\tinterface LanePool {\n117\t  maxLanes: number;           // from execution.max_parallel\n118\t  activeLanes: Map<string, Lane>;  // epicId → Lane\n119\t  pendingEpics: string[];     // ordered queue of epics to schedule\n120\t  mergeQueue: string[];       // epics waiting to merge (serialized)\n121\t}\n122\t\n123\tinterface Lane {\n124\t  epicId: string;\n125\t  worktreePath: string;\n126\t  branch: string;\n127\t  engineInstance: Promise<EngineResult>;  // async workflow execution\n128\t  status: 'executing' | 'merging' | 'validating' | 'done' | 'failed';\n129\t}\n130\t```\n131\t\n132\t**Scheduling:** When a lane frees up, the pool picks the next epic from `pendingEpics` that has no dependency on any `activeLane` epic. For MVP, dependency is determined by epic ordering — epic N can only run if no epic < N is still active (except completed ones). Post-MVP: explicit DAG from epic declarations.\n133\t\n134\t**Concurrency model:** `Promise.race()` on active lanes. When any lane completes, its result is processed (merge queued), and next epic scheduled.\n135\t\n136\t```typescript\n137\twhile (pendingEpics.length > 0 || activeLanes.size > 0) {\n138\t  // Fill lanes up to max\n139\t  while (activeLanes.size < maxLanes && hasReadyEpic()) {\n140\t    const epic = nextReadyEpic();\n141\t    const lane = await createLane(epic);\n142\t    activeLanes.set(epic.id, lane);\n143\t  }\n144\t  // Wait for any lane to complete\n145\t  const completed = await Promise.race(\n146\t    [...activeLanes.values()].map(l => l.engineInstance)\n147\t  );\n148\t  // Process completion: queue merge, free lane\n149\t  await processLaneCompletion(completed);\n150\t}"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01P6VJWwxyDkdUjYM8CN6t2V","session_id":"8a461711-53e2-475a-88dd-c7013f6080c5","uuid":"5eab9122-8c40-4073-a1f1-6f47f525859d","timestamp":"2026-04-03T17:09:12.864Z"}
